result.execSummary:
The defendant Zachery M Muehe was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[ma] Case called at 10:46 AM 
Defendant Zachery M Muehe in court with Attorney Jeffrey Jacob De La Rosa.  Jeffrey Martin Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.

Maximum penalties are recited; Constitutional rights are reviewed; plea of " NO CONTEST " entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance is verified.  The Court accepts the plea, finds the Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2

Sentencing arguments given by Counsel 

On Count #1, the Court withholds sentence and places the Defendant on Probation for 1 year, with conditions:
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment per Agent
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, or counseling per Agent
--no possession of any dangerous weapon, the Court will allow possession of weapons for hunting if/as authorized by Agent
--no acts or threats of violence
--no possession or ingestion of alcohol
--to comply with DNA sample provision 

Separate from the conditions of Probation, the Court orders payment of costs, fees and surcharges through the Clerk of Courts Office. [Clerk calculates this total to be:$443 and includes this amount on  the payment slip] The Court grants installment payments of $40 per month beginning on 7/1/19 and on the 1st day of the month thereafter until paid in full.  Non-payment will result in  8 days in Jail with Huber privileges.

The Court authorizes expungement upon completion of full 12 months of Probation
